SIMPLE: olian
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Æolian
<hw>⟦AE⟧*o"li*an</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Aeolius</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to
⟦AE⟧olia or ⟦AE⟧olis, in Asia Minor, colonized by the Greeks, or to its
inhabitants; ⟦ae⟧olic; <as>as, the <ex>⟦AE⟧olian</ex>
dialect</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to ⟦AE⟧olus, the mythic god of the winds;
a⟦eum⟧rial.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Viewless forms the <qex>⟦ae⟧olian</qex> organ play.</q>
<rj><qau>Campbell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Relating to or caused by wind; <as>as,
<ex>aeolian</ex> erosion</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>⟦AE⟧olian attachment</b></col>, <cd>a contrivance often
attached to a pianoforte, which prolongs the vibrations, increases the
volume of sound, etc., by forcing a stream of air upon the strings.</cd>
<au>Moore.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>⟦AE⟧olian harp</b></col>,
<col><b>⟦AE⟧olian lyre</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a musical instrument
consisting of a box, on or in which are stretched strings, on which the
wind acts to produce the notes; -- usually placed at an open
window.</cd> <au>Moore.</au> -- <col><b>⟦AE⟧olian mode</b></col>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>one of the ancient Greek and early ecclesiastical
modes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 27 --></p>

<p><ent>Aeolian</ent>⟦br⟧
